  <div id="me">
    <div class="section-title">
      <h2>About Me</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="about-text">
      <p>
        I am a creative, a mother, and a licensed clinical social worker. I obtained my master’s degree in social work from the University of Pennsylvania in 2007 and have since specialized in helping children and families navigate transitions, heal from trauma, and develop deeper relationships. Most recently, I worked as a teacher at an arts based preschool, provided mental health consultation to public preschools, and provided therapy to children and families in San Francisco. I also have a deep love of glitter, thread, and imagination.
      </p><p>
        As a therapist and a mother, I understand and deeply value the power of play and creative space as a way to feed and develop the connection between a child and parent. By following a child’s lead in play, validating the child’s feelings and ideas, and shutting out all other distractions we demonstrate to our children at a very fundamental and tangible level that we value who they are and what they care about. My own personal experience, as well as contemporary research, also demonstrate that a child’s understanding that their parent truly SEES them and values them as an individual has an impact on every other parental task. Having a strong well-fed mutual connection with our child does not mean that the child isn’t going to do the developmental testing work they need to do. However, the families I work with, as well as my own, testify that the everyday navigation of life and developmental needs of the family feels lighter when the connection between the child and parent has been recently nourished.
      </p>
